            "author_association": "NONE",
            "body": "Good point, thanks. I am thinking of two type of tags, or two type of tag assignment. Let's say \"message specific tags\" and \"topic tags\". \r\n\"Message specific tags\" are assigned to a single message. For example, if someone announces a meeting. This could be tagged as \"announcements\", \"important\" or whatever.\r\nOn the other hand, \"topic tags\" are assigned or inherited automatically by means of simple heuristics. For example, if a message is sent very close in time to another, they are considered to belong to the same conversation, so the second message should inherit its topic-tags.  Then, if a group is discussing what movie they are going to see, the first message is tagged as \"movie\", and all messages that follow are tagged automatically. This automatic inheritance could be cleared after a timeout.\r\n\r\nWrong assignments could be addressed with the rating system. A tag could be voted positively or negatively by any group member. Tags could disappear after their rating falls below a given negative threshold.",
